–1335":"1295–1335","1313–1362":"1313–1362","–1324":"–1324","–Female":"Deceased","1265–1311":"1265–1311","1260–1297":"1260–1297","about 1280":"about 1282","1297":"1297","1362":"1362","1295":"1295","1282":"1282","1260":"1260","1290":"1290","1315":"1315","about 1307":"about 1307","1313":"1313","1335":"1335","1324":"1324","20 June 1324":"20 June 1324","1311":"1311","26 June 1324":"26 June 1324","1265":"1265","about 1313":"about 1313","1317":"1317","Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Pembrokeshire, Wales","Luppitt, Devon, England":"Luppitt, Devon, England","Moulsford, Berkshire, England":"Moulsford, Berkshire, England","Berkshire, England":"Berkshire, England","Herefordshire, England":"Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom","Pembroke, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Pembroke, Pembrokeshire, Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Carru","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Olivier, Antoine, Arnaud, Marcel, Marie-Noelle, Pierre, Regine.","French (<b>Carré</b>): from Old French <i>carré</i> ‘square’, applied as a nickname for a squat, thickset man, or a habitational name from any of several places in various parts of France called (Le) Carré, named with the same word.","French: metonymic occupational name for a cartwright or carter, from the dialect word <i>carre</i> ‘cart, wagon’ (see 3 below)."],"variants":[{"name":"Carr","meanings":["Irish: shortened Anglicized form of <b>Ó Carra</b> ‘descendant of <i>Carra</i>’, a personal name from the adjective <i>corr</i> ‘pointed’, explained as meaning ‘spear’. As an Ulster surname, <i>Carr</i> was often confused with Scottish   Kerr  .","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of <b>Mac Giolla Chathair</b>, a Donegal name meaning ‘son of <i>Giolla Cathair</i>’ or ‘the servant (i.e. devotee) of Saint <i>Cathar</i>’. Cathar was a priest and bishop, otherwise unknown.","Irish: in Galway, a shortened Anglicized form of <b>Mac Giolla Chéire</b>, see   Keary  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":8,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":33,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir John Carru was born about 1282, in Moulsford, Berkshire, England, his father, Nicholas Carew III, was 19 and his mother, Amicia Peverell, was 23. He married Joan Talbot about 1307, in Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. He died on 26 June 1324, in Berkshire, England, at the age of 43."},"et":{"about 1280–26 June 1324":"umbes 1282–26. juuni 1324","1282–1324":"1282–1324","1295–1335":"1295–1335","1313–1362":"1313–1362","–1324":"–1324","–Female":"Surnud","1265–1311":"1265–1311","1260–1297":"1260–1297","about 1280":"umbes 1282","1297":"1297","1362":"1362","1295":"1295","1282":"1282","1260":"1260","1290":"1290","1315":"1315","about 1307":"umbes 1307","1313":"1313","1335":"1335","1324":"1324","20 June 1324":"20. juuni 1324","1311":"1311","26 June 1324":"26. juuni 1324","1265":"1265","about 1313":"umbes 1313","1317":"1317","Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Pembrokeshire, Wales","Luppitt, Devon, England":"Luppitt, Devon, England","Moulsford, Berkshire, England":"Moulsford, Berkshire, England","Berkshire, England":"Berkshire, England","Herefordshire, England":"Herefordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Pembroke, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Pembroke, Pembrokeshire, Wales"},"fi":{"about 1280–26 June 1324":"noin 1282–26. kesäkuuta 1324","1282–1324":"1282–1324","1295–1335":"1295–1335","1313–1362":"1313–1362","–1324":"–1324","–Female":"Kuollut","1265–1311":"1265–1311","1260–1297":"1260–1297","about 1280":"noin 1282","1297":"1297","1362":"1362","1295":"1295","1282":"1282","1260":"1260","1290":"1290","1315":"1315","about 1307":"noin 1307","1313":"1313","1335":"1335","1324":"1324","20 June 1324":"20. kesäkuuta 1324","1311":"1311","26 June 1324":"26. kesäkuuta 1324","1265":"1265","about 1313":"noin 1313","1317":"1317","Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Pembrokeshire, 